{
  "id": "f1",
  "front": "What is a group in abstract algebra?",
  "back": "A group is a set G equipped with a binary operation that combines any two elements to form a third element, satisfying four conditions: closure, associativity, identity, and invertibility."
},
{
  "id": "f2",
  "front": "What are the four group axioms?",
  "back": "1. Closure: For all a, b in G, the result of the operation a • b is also in G.\n2. Associativity: For all a, b, c in G, (a • b) • c = a • (b • c).\n3. Identity: There exists an element e in G such that for every element a in G, e • a = a • e = a.\n4. Invertibility: For each a in G, there exists an element b in G such that a • b = b • a = e."
},
{
  "id": "f3",
  "front": "What is an abelian group?",
  "back": "An abelian group is a group where the operation is commutative. That is, for all a, b in G, a • b = b • a."
},
{
  "id": "f4",
  "front": "What is the order of a group?",
  "back": "The order of a group G, denoted |G|, is the number of elements in G. If the group is infinite, it is said to have infinite order."
},
{
  "id": "f5",
  "front": "What is a subgroup?",
  "back": "A subgroup H of a group G is a subset of G that is itself a group under the same operation as G."
}
